# Contributing Standards

## Git workflow

- Branch from **`dev`**, never from `main`
- Branch name: `your-name/short-description` (lowercase, hyphens)
  - e.g. `alice/add-user-migration`, `bob/fix-dashboard-loading`

## Commit messages — Conventional Commits

```
<type>(<scope>): <description>
```

| Type | When to use |
|---|---|
| `feat` | New feature |
| `fix` | Bug fix |
| `refactor` | No feature/fix change |
| `docs` | Documentation only |
| `test` | Tests only |
| `chore` | Build, deps, config |
| `perf` | Performance improvement |

Use present-tense imperative: `add user validation`, not `added user validation`.

## Naming conventions

| Thing | Style | Example |
|---|---|---|
| Files/modules | snake_case | `access_management.py` |
| Classes | PascalCase | `SisenseClient` |
| Functions/methods | snake_case | `get_user()` |
| Constants | UPPER_SNAKE | `MAX_RETRIES` |
| Private | `_` prefix | `_make_request()` |

## Docstrings — NumPy style (required)

Every public method must have a NumPy-style docstring. Include these sections as applicable: summary line, short description (2–6 lines), `Parameters`, `Returns`, optionally `Raises` and `Notes`.

```python
def create_user(self, name: str, email: str, role: str = "viewer") -> dict[str, Any]:
    """Create a new user in Sisense.

    Sends a POST request to create a user account. The role name is resolved
    to its internal Sisense role ID before submission.

    Parameters
    ----------
    name : str
        The full name of the user.
    email : str
        The email address of the user.
    role : str, optional
        Role to assign. One of ``"viewer"``, ``"dashboardDesigner"``, ``"sysAdmin"``.

    Returns
    -------
    dict[str, Any]
        The created user object returned by the API, or ``{"error": "..."}`` on failure.
    """
```

- Always include **type hints** on parameters and return values.
- Avoid restating what the code already says.
- **Never** mention MCP, tools, LLMs, agents, orchestration, or any external system in docstrings.
- Do **not** include `Example:` or `Examples` blocks in docstrings.

## Update payload docstrings

For methods that accept an update/patch payload, the docstring must:
- State that updates must be provided inside the payload parameter (e.g., `user_data`).
- List supported fields using **canonical Sisense payload field names**.
- Clearly state: only fields provided are updated; omitted fields are not modified.
- If role or group names are resolved to IDs, briefly describe the resolution behavior.

```python
def update_user(self, user_id: str, user_data: dict[str, Any]) -> dict[str, Any]:
    """Update an existing user's properties.

    Only fields present in ``user_data`` are modified; omitted fields retain
    their current values. If ``role`` is provided as a name, it is resolved to
    its internal ``roleId`` before the request is sent.

    Parameters
    ----------
    user_id : str
        The unique identifier of the user to update.
    user_data : dict[str, Any]
        Payload containing fields to update. Supported fields:

        - ``userName`` – login username
        - ``email`` – email address
        - ``firstName`` / ``lastName`` – display name parts
        - ``role`` – role name (resolved to ``roleId`` automatically)
        - ``groups`` – list of group names (resolved to group IDs)

    Returns
    -------
    dict[str, Any]
        The updated user object, or ``{"error": "..."}`` on failure.
    """
```
